    "narrative_summary": "Within this archive, Adidas exposure rises from event-linked sports visibility into full-spectrum brand ownership. In the 1990s and early 2000s, Adidas appears mainly as embedded sporting infrastructure: the official World Cup match ball, three-stripe team kit details, and branded footwear visible inside global football broadcasts. That makes the brand present but still secondary to the event itself.\n\nBy 2012\u20132017, the exposure pattern changes sharply. Adidas becomes the subject rather than the backdrop: Team GB Olympic kit launch material, the 2014 Messi/Battle Pack campaign, Yeezy product storytelling, NMD launch film, and Parley sustainability content all move the brand into hero-shot territory. Exposure becomes more controlled, more logo-forward, and more diversified across performance, fashion, and purpose.\n\nOverall, the trend in this corpus is clear: Adidas shifts from intermittent tournament visibility in the 1990s/2000s to denser, more intentional, and more narratively central exposure in the mid-2010s. The strongest concentration is 2012\u20132017, when the brand spans elite sport, cultural collaborations, and sustainability messaging rather than relying only on on-field presence.",
